Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Documentation", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768980666861076`*^9, 
  3.9768980688080997`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b6d1810f-13b5-fa43-b77d-\
2de9f747113a"],

Cell["\<\
Mathematica has a large library of documentation including which is easily \
accessible by going to the Help tab and clicking the documentation. You can \
also press the F1 key and it will bring you to the documentation home page. \
If you highlight over text and press the F1 key, it will search the \
Mathematica documentation for your highlighted text. 

If you chose to download the documentation locally, you will not need access \
to the internet in order to navigate the documentation. In addition, the \
documentation includes a number of interactive notebook tutorials that you \
can access from the homepage and open directly in Mathematica. If you do not \
have the documentation installed, trying to open the documentation in \
Mathematica will open the documentation in your web browser. There, you can \
also download other Mathematica tutorials from the documentation. 

If you are ever unsure of how to do something in Mathematica, check the \
documentation. If that doesn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t work, searching online can \
also help as there is a widespread community of Mathematica users. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768980666861076`*^9, 3.9768980959924126`*^9}, {
  3.976898127245882*^9, 3.976898139187004*^9}, {3.9768981783921223`*^9, 
  3.976898202128599*^9}, {3.9768982357254906`*^9, 3.9768982802401466`*^9}, {
  3.976898346184189*^9, 3.9768984235956917`*^9}, {3.993724793071039*^9, 
  3.993724976964775*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"724763e6-f0ed-4941-a2d0-\
ef32e714433e"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Errors", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976362996896698*^9, 
  3.9763629988590584`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"8dbd4b80-15f7-4f4c-9f2e-\
883cdbf28a1f"],

Cell["\<\
When Mathematica is unable to perform an action, it will still give an \
output. However, it will also give an error. As an example, Evaluate the code \
below to see what it looks like:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976362996896698*^9, 3.976363072658657*^9}, {
  3.9763631469021454`*^9, 3.9763632017280827`*^9}, {3.9763632724247246`*^9, 
  3.9763632959167213`*^9}, {3.976363405594818*^9, 3.976363410874132*^9}, {
  3.976363521077856*^9, 
  3.9763635212764435`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6cdc41bf-7fa6-6746-9265-\
678436c9380a"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"1", "/", "0", " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"generates", " ", "an", " ", "error"}], "*)"}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976362996896698*^9, 3.976363072658657*^9}, {
  3.9763631469021454`*^9, 3.9763632017280827`*^9}, {3.9763632724247246`*^9, 
  3.9763633832791595`*^9}, {3.9763634612478466`*^9, 3.9763634928682785`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[8]:=",ExpressionUUID->"c92bff20-e27f-fe46-8b7a-cb1873f9fc01"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "You should see some error text: ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  TemplateBox[{
   "Power", "infy", 
    "\"Infinite expression \\!\\(\\*FractionBox[\\\"1\\\", \\\"0\\\"]\\) \
encountered.\"", 2, 8, 3, 28502280489868705666, "Local"},
   "MessageTemplate",
   BaseStyle->"MSG"]], "Message",
  CellChangeTimes->{3.9763634934025764`*^9},ExpressionUUID->
  "f8b00f73-cd5b-a442-9af7-c7168250ea89"],
 ".  The three dots will allow you too look more closely at what the error is \
and the little blue icon will link you to the Mathematica documentation \
associated with that error. \n\nNotice also that Mathematica still gave the \
output \[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]ComplexInfinity\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] which \
is technically correct, but ultimately the answer should be \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]undefined\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote].  "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976363525190325*^9, 3.9763635534780655`*^9}, {
   3.9763636685324345`*^9, 3.976363702323744*^9}, {3.9763638052522297`*^9, 
   3.9763639280821533`*^9}, {3.976363970011118*^9, 3.976364045739847*^9}, 
   3.976364084421118*^9},ExpressionUUID->"a4dffb45-b18e-334e-91f8-\
c13fa4d05f47"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell[" Troubleshooting", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9763605269578304`*^9, 3.9763605405599556`*^9}, 
   3.976362897395752*^9},ExpressionUUID->"d07e6d95-e1f4-d84a-9cab-\
703cb4cfa59d"],

Cell["\<\
There are a few different tools you can use to troubleshoot/debug your code. \
We will include some details on how to do this a bit later in the guide. \
However, there are a couple basic troubleshooting tools we will are going to \
introduce now as they are essential. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9763605269578304`*^9, 3.976360580211254*^9}, {
   3.9763606573490295`*^9, 3.9763611351387253`*^9}, {3.976361166590292*^9, 
   3.976361203956505*^9}, {3.976361247466671*^9, 3.9763612728024406`*^9}, {
   3.976361469973057*^9, 3.9763614805060215`*^9}, 3.976361523449379*^9, {
   3.976361988873226*^9, 3.976362060277151*^9}, {3.9763640973649178`*^9, 
   3.9763641622824745`*^9}, {3.9763642170831356`*^9, 3.976364360157648*^9}, {
   3.976364419040922*^9, 3.9763645086963787`*^9}, {3.9763645430575523`*^9, 
   3.9763645883778515`*^9}, {3.9763646185616264`*^9, 3.976364672188118*^9}, {
   3.9763647236279125`*^9, 3.9763647295840225`*^9}, {3.976364803962988*^9, 
   3.976364848831375*^9}, {3.9763650953115807`*^9, 3.976365116520603*^9}, {
   3.9763651738885746`*^9, 
   3.976365183824669*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"75f36611-97c6-aa4a-a249-\
5e2b582fdcd1"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The first tool is the Abort command.  Once you tell Mathematica to evaluate \
a code cell, it will not evaluate any other code until after the code cell \
has finished evaluating. This can be problematic if you need to make a change \
to your code while it is evaluating or if you have made a mistake somewhere.  \
For example, if you have a block of code that includes an infinite loop, you \
will not be able to make any changes until Mathematica goes through enough \
iterations to overflow the memory. \n\nThe Abort command is the failsafe that \
allows you to stop Mathematica mid-evaluation.  You can use the Abort command \
mid-evaluation by either clicking the abort button at the top left of the \
screen ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  GraphicsBox[
   TagBox[RasterBox[CompressedData["
1:eJztl0tT2lAUx51202W/QnddMCIICMpDVCwSEpggiVB8JBIeofIMKkptawc6
nWmnjOi0dfqaTtvP4KoLl2y76rfpkWjmirzCtJDp5D+HzM25B+aXy8k9595j
M2Ts1tjYWOEOXEhmx5nPM6XAXbgJpgvJeJqLLqUFLs7lzextcN6Hjw0+F+MZ
VapUqVL1H8k+O49TMXI1J9cwcsNqs4+Eec7lie5+SBz8aGvxx998kUKnWbD1
bG0k5KHE8y5U/lVhfFwb2XrdJYagE8PHZovvUAbvylaYfymOo6XPukmTRqOZ
djyQFj8Yfepf20a/QnMHN3/W2tTQsB2LJHCabS6S2Vv0bWiuBKmCh7OGKSuM
PcFkT2yCICiKGhq2C0HtJP9qUWnYGJXqiQ15ohxsyNtI+s2CN9IT20Px67n6
yLFXEtUZJ6ad0EtgkMPFVz8PP/1GLVH+jsLr9Aa7y88W3/eJnclk2gJ08vfE
ZrdP57EwioQF+RZm0YxmBxrmJrk+V7tSqTQajVqt1hIGHvDD7ADYF1UjVxf3
EFFe6lFbbNO0U4qBdNrc/dgnNo7jZ2dnQFitViUnjMEDfpgdDBsM1lxvMPeJ
DTskt/dFVm7TNH1+fg6c5XIZbuEKY/CAXy4zik2Es1AQ+8Q2mu3LmwdyX0mG
YRpNHR8fiwPwDMAsYZMbJd3klKwkgQUPJatydxKe5xtXSqVSgzGL2BT3zGSZ
Rd+1OU/4JvOT018TOgMaZp3zQrsidwMUBAGY4Tows4i9lj0KsGV3IGZf8E8a
p6XNhOYOUXO66csMsThm3UEoTPC8jPBWCVWSeJhrW2JQhZIvlFMlRVsKxHpi
B9h9pWFLdQc2Q73RIqFCYkhlFFpBpWHb5nGxa4UWheIORc5x7QTkMLTfYu8K
/8jIsddzR9cOWfmTa0+x4NM0eyf0mNYSs8zs/Du8TvKFUt2Oirk6pEds/2uX
GJeHHD621WqDM3iXUzDkRqcppnCCBdjhM6tSpUqVKlV/UX8ALz/gGg==
     "], {{0, 24.}, {36.6, 0}}, {0, 255},
     ColorFunction->RGBColor,
     ImageResolution->{120., 120.},
     RasterInterpolation->"High"],
    BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
    Selectable->False],
   DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
   ImageSize->Automatic,
   ImageSizeRaw->{36.6, 24.},
   PlotRange->{{0, 36.6}, {0, 24.}}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->
  "4a5f66f1-93b1-2046-a988-1f389fe6af09"],
 ", or you can press ",
 StyleBox["Alt + . ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "on your keyboard. Below, I have programmed an infinite loop. Try evaluating \
it and then using the Abort command (",
 StyleBox["Alt + .",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ") to stop the evaluation: "
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9763605269578304`*^9, 3.976360580211254*^9}, {
   3.9763606573490295`*^9, 3.9763611351387253`*^9}, {3.976361166590292*^9, 
   3.976361203956505*^9}, {3.976361247466671*^9, 3.9763612728024406`*^9}, {
   3.976361469973057*^9, 3.9763614805060215`*^9}, 3.976361523449379*^9, {
   3.976361988873226*^9, 3.976362060277151*^9}, {3.9763640973649178`*^9, 
   3.9763641622824745`*^9}, {3.9763642170831356`*^9, 3.976364360157648*^9}, {
   3.976364419040922*^9, 3.9763645086963787`*^9}, {3.9763645430575523`*^9, 
   3.9763645883778515`*^9}, {3.9763646185616264`*^9, 3.976364672188118*^9}, {
   3.9763647236279125`*^9, 3.9763647269763813`*^9}, {3.9763651653569355`*^9, 
   3.9763651676741123`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"aeae4fb1-40fe-9a4d-ab25-\
df6437e50130"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"While", "[", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"0", "<", "1"}], ",", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"k", "=", "2"}], ";"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", "]"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9763605269578304`*^9, 3.976360580211254*^9}, {
  3.9763606573490295`*^9, 3.9763611642280655`*^9}, {3.9763620660531693`*^9, 
  3.976362086986988*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[1]:=",ExpressionUUID->"5edbe935-5042-2744-a607-2104c2c1b50a"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "A couple things to note, for some keyboards the abort command only works \
for the",
 StyleBox[" LEFT ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Alt key. Notice also on the right-hand side that the cell bracket becomes \
bold when Mathematica is evaluating code. \n\nThe final tool we will \
introduce here is the quit Kernel command. It isn\[CloseCurlyQuote]t super \
important that you understand what the Kernel is or why it needs to be \
restarted. What you do need to know is that this command is basically the \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]Turn it off and turn it on again\
\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] solution in Mathematica. You can access this command \
by simply evaluating the command ",
 StyleBox["Quit[] ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "in an input cell or by going to the toolbar on the top left of the window \
and going to ",
 StyleBox["Evaluation > Quit Kernel > Local",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". \n\nKeep in mind that this will clear any and all variables and outputs \
you have declared from memory, so you will have to re-evaluate all of that \
code again if you are using them. The main thing to remember is this: ",
 StyleBox["If you are not sure what could be wrong with your code, try \
quiting the kernel. \n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9763621247408504`*^9, 3.976362190113001*^9}, {
  3.976362227951439*^9, 3.976362313552841*^9}, {3.976362384584896*^9, 
  3.976362395379135*^9}, {3.976362460456299*^9, 3.976362559241068*^9}, {
  3.9763625996409607`*^9, 3.976362832953575*^9}, {3.976362890435795*^9, 
  3.976362893899004*^9}, {3.9763641385714073`*^9, 
  3.9763641433858376`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d978294c-4315-ac44-b853-\
97e5332dbf0f"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Comments in code", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9762788884046345`*^9, 3.976278993810583*^9}, 
   3.976279033488989*^9, {3.9762792158151207`*^9, 
   3.9762792221603165`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b1ac9539-0d85-1248-ab28-\
54fc3db7cffe"],

Cell["\<\
While Mathematica allows you to type in text boxes which will not evaluate as \
code, it is still good practice to include comments in your input boxes. \
Mathematica uses (* *) to denote comments:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9762788884046345`*^9, 3.976278993810583*^9}, 
   3.976279033488989*^9, {3.9762792158151207`*^9, 
   3.9762793019355164`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"63c67412-6324-684d-9bec-\
50a9be178593"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"(*", 
  RowBox[{"Comments", " ", "that", " ", 
   RowBox[{"won", "'"}], "t", " ", "be", " ", "evaluated", " ", "as", " ", 
   "code"}], "*)"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9762788884046345`*^9, 3.976278993810583*^9}, 
   3.976279033488989*^9, {3.9762792158151207`*^9, 3.9762793218096867`*^9}, {
   3.9762793670141354`*^9, 
   3.976279367674671*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0fa0f908-1dee-3c4e-a9bf-\
94f90418cd9a"],

Cell["\<\
You can also highlight text and then press Alt + ? to comment in/out a block \
of code\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9762793306955013`*^9, 
  3.976279373691601*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"dd2bac24-4f7e-324d-b15a-\
3c7eb5d7be76"]
}, Closed]]
}, Open  ]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Variables and Basic Functions", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9762788884046345`*^9, 3.976278993810583*^9}, {
  3.9762790340895214`*^9, 3.976279046761484*^9}, {3.976279106066147*^9, 
  3.976279112772665*^9}, {3.976279191239517*^9, 3.976279198724024*^9}, {
  3.9762794823125*^9, 3.9762794832339287`*^9}, {3.976279753915844*^9, 
  3.976279776443733*^9}, {3.9762798314829025`*^9, 3.9762798322848167`*^9}, {
  3.9763594053980675`*^9, 3.9763594128312473`*^9}, {3.976359672082884*^9, 
  3.9763596861535683`*^9}, {3.976365297747225*^9, 3.9763653080156994`*^9}, {
  3.9766222003551064`*^9, 3.9766222010167065`*^9}, {3.976898226563446*^9, 
  3.976898227157507*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"40984552-4a12-9943-95b3-\
6bbe2757415e"],

Cell["\<\
Like other programming languages, Mathematica allows you define variables by \
writing <VariableName> = <value>:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976359533988247*^9, 3.9763595754165936`*^9}, {
  3.976359606865341*^9, 3.9763596125892124`*^9}, {3.9763597991548843`*^9, 
  3.976359805132225*^9}, {3.9766249324683685`*^9, 3.9766249434589043`*^9}, {
  3.976897867750759*^9, 
  3.9768978695848713`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"40e8180b-9a90-354d-b5a6-\
18856c85a0e7"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"variable", " ", "=", " ", "20"}], ";"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "the", " ", "variable"}], " ", "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"variable", "  ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"output", " ", "variable", " ", "value"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9762788884046345`*^9, 3.976278993810583*^9}, {
  3.9762790340895214`*^9, 3.976279046761484*^9}, {3.976279106066147*^9, 
  3.976279112772665*^9}, {3.976279191239517*^9, 3.976279198724024*^9}, {
  3.9762794823125*^9, 3.9762794832339287`*^9}, {3.976279753915844*^9, 
  3.976279776443733*^9}, {3.9762798314829025`*^9, 3.9762798322848167`*^9}, {
  3.9763594069974823`*^9, 3.9763594070264816`*^9}, {3.9763596154233246`*^9, 
  3.976359641733822*^9}, {3.9763598116581097`*^9, 3.9763598124980183`*^9}, {
  3.9763598646141815`*^9, 3.976359870645838*^9}, {3.976359953574068*^9, 
  3.9763599639415016`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[9]:=",ExpressionUUID->"aa2ffc01-0b3a-644f-8e89-903f147ac9bb"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Be careful when naming your variables as Mathematica has some pre-defined \
constants. Attempting to declare pre-defined constants as a variable will \
result in in error. One way you can tell whether or not a function is already \
defined is by the color of the text. Undefined variables are in ",
 StyleBox["light blue",
  FontWeight->"Bold",
  FontColor->RGBColor[
   0.6901960784313725, 0.6745098039215687, 0.9764705882352941]],
 ", while defined variables are in ",
 StyleBox["white",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Mathematica also has a way for you to look-up constants and even handle \
physical units, which we will address later in this guide. (REF?)"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9763600128025208`*^9, 3.9763601461893387`*^9}, {
  3.976360357959549*^9, 3.976360391554182*^9}, {3.9766247845208473`*^9, 
  3.9766248260092564`*^9}, {3.9766249501854057`*^9, 3.9766250027556667`*^9}, {
  3.976625260068676*^9, 
  3.9766254046725464`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6570536f-10bf-854b-b2d1-\
03f5bf979d5b"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{"myVar", " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "notice", " ", "the", " ", "text", " ", "is", " ", "blue", " ", "because", 
    " ", "the", " ", "variable", " ", 
    RowBox[{"hasn", "'"}], "t", " ", "been", " ", "defined"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"Pi", " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "The", " ", "ratio", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", "circumference", " ", 
    "of", " ", "a", " ", "circle", " ", "to", " ", "its", " ", "diameter"}], 
   "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"I", " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   TemplateBox[<|"boxes" -> FormBox[
       SqrtBox["-1"], TraditionalForm], "errors" -> {}, "input" -> 
     "\\sqrt{-1}", "state" -> "Boxes"|>,
    "TeXAssistantTemplate"], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"Pi", "=", " ", "3", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
    "error", " ", "generated", " ", "when", " ", "trying", " ", "to", " ", 
     "define", " ", "Pi"}], " ", "=", " ", "3"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9763600128025208`*^9, 3.9763601461893387`*^9}, {
  3.976360357959549*^9, 3.976360497579914*^9}, {3.9766248013189983`*^9, 
  3.9766248147103863`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0f1cb62b-65ad-184a-b7f7-\
e598a4ad074e"],

Cell["\<\
Once you have defined and evaluated variables you can use them at any point \
in your calculations. Mathematica can perform any basic calculator functions \
using the standard characters on your keyboard: + (add), - (subtract), * \
(multiply), / (divide), ^ (exponent). Try defining a few variables below and \
performing these simple operations:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365436435215*^9, 3.976365455965885*^9}, {
   3.976365494172184*^9, 3.9763655874665375`*^9}, {3.976366064886591*^9, 
   3.976366125368452*^9}, 3.9766222040698185`*^9, {3.9766247668768406`*^9, 
   3.976624777918894*^9}, {3.976624830574629*^9, 
   3.976624918286068*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"089aecd7-c9a2-f84e-bd5b-\
a5c8fcc4d976"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"(*", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Your", " ", "code", " ", "here"}], "*)"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365436435215*^9, 3.976365455965885*^9}, {
   3.976365494172184*^9, 3.9763655874665375`*^9}, {3.976366064886591*^9, 
   3.976366125368452*^9}, 3.9766222040698185`*^9, {3.9766247668768406`*^9, 
   3.976624777918894*^9}, {3.976624830574629*^9, 
   3.976624925901882*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1ec14d5f-3d0e-9241-a80e-\
49503af9797d"],

Cell["\<\
Mathematica also allows for typesetting within the code. This allows for \
cleaner looking input. For example, using Ctrl + / will create a fraction bar \
where you can write code in the numerator and the denominator. Ctrl + 6 will \
allow you to input superscripts which behave as exponents when evaluated. \
There are also a number of other typesetting tricks, and we will touch upon \
them more in Section II.  Here are some examples, feel free to mess with them \
or try something out. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976625167095028*^9, 3.9766252492925262`*^9}, {
  3.976625427460882*^9, 3.9766254395536823`*^9}, {3.976625508033922*^9, 
  3.9766256961898212`*^9}, {3.9766259727446423`*^9, 3.976626012604677*^9}, {
  3.976626065420435*^9, 
  3.9766260817749557`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"9f639fee-47f1-9b48-959e-\
7c615f4e12b5"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  FractionBox["3", "4"], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
    "Create", " ", "a", " ", "fraction", " ", "bar", " ", "using", " ", 
     "ctrl"}], " ", "+", " ", "/"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  SuperscriptBox["2", "2"], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"create", " ", "an", " ", "exponet", " ", "using", " ", "ctrl"}], 
    " ", "+", " ", "6"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976625167095028*^9, 3.9766252492925262`*^9}, {
  3.976625427460882*^9, 3.9766254395536823`*^9}, {3.976625508033922*^9, 
  3.9766257014868393`*^9}, {3.9766260187320557`*^9, 3.9766260594916973`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[1]:=",ExpressionUUID->"add9f6e3-5414-4143-a6e1-366203c730a0"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Of course, just like your calculator, Mathematica also do more complex and \
specific calculations using pre-defined functions. Functions in Mathematica \
have the form ",
 StyleBox["Function[<parameters>]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ". Notice, the pre-defined function is always capitalized! Your parameters \
will depend on which function you are using, if you are not sure what \
parameters you need look for the documentation of the command using F1 or \
clicking ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  GraphicsBox[
   TagBox[RasterBox[CompressedData["
1:eJztVEsvA2EUbdhY2rKzb7Q1U4Nq+jC0HTUdMy0SStBH2qbVaSW0REKC0HiE
DdKVxA4LCxIbGxs7P8De33DMVUGbtrqycPJNc++55zuduTPf7ZhbkCNNOp0u
24IfeXbJkcnM5pRWJIFUNhZNhUOe1GI4Gs70zDWDbMfVhus9tvzjD8A2MsbP
pAdDOSy7PP3J9zt4pMRD8LVUDvtocGT7Sjp+cOVOefUAy7t1KZ89CatFV3oX
PNKh5RPw7rVzpL79O+dEtKKVWLixTqmdTLf+C5CCtIdWjL02/XeAxx9VtPId
3pfrqwDi6laiKOZLSCaTRqMRuyzqjjkQQiAIApUURalpZTKZzCUwDIPtJodn
+PbVunSE2GAwUAmymlaAokGWZbICWCnYyXIIeJ6nKmQ1rSAOaoD4w0ecHCw+
GqwDiCVJoipkNa1+9LYvtua+eMYDktVv265q8Pv9tAVWuCuK4/E4VSGrv+0s
y2Jv15APt4Q3SFboXv1tR+DRwHEcPSCsPNcv3EyGrKgK2W/bbh6POAtXMPx8
gw23veGvnXEIZpdim8/TcUbQIwb12kkEj0PnTGwSj7S6FZ13zAFMEldiw60W
aFaIe7fD6xfEUwky8FgVrWzeAIZVOU8DqpzHyKqo/0c9eAM46Rpz
     "], {{0, 15.6}, {15., 0}}, {0, 255},
     ColorFunction->RGBColor,
     ImageResolution->{120., 120.},
     RasterInterpolation->"High"],
    BoxForm`ImageTag["Byte", ColorSpace -> "RGB", Interleaving -> True],
    Selectable->False],
   DefaultBaseStyle->"ImageGraphics",
   ImageSize->Automatic,
   ImageSizeRaw->{15., 15.6},
   PlotRange->{{0, 15.}, {0, 15.6}}]], "Input",ExpressionUUID->
  "d03319bd-423d-eb47-9c95-b34b1893cdd2"],
 ". Common calculations such as sine, cosine, square root, and logarithms are \
pre-defined in Mathematica. For the most part, they work as you would expect:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976625167095028*^9, 3.9766252492925262`*^9}, {
   3.976625427460882*^9, 3.9766254395536823`*^9}, {3.976625508033922*^9, 
   3.976625691710966*^9}, 3.976626016406105*^9, {3.9766260981979046`*^9, 
   3.976626245479927*^9}, {3.976626445336857*^9, 3.9766264526377544`*^9}, {
   3.976626487782814*^9, 3.976626557942606*^9}, {3.976898311806013*^9, 
   3.9768983313602104`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"497da634-cd24-384d-9b17-\
d5598d72c0b9"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
   FractionBox["Pi", "2"], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"sin", " ", "of", " ", 
    FractionBox["\[Pi]", "2"]}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Cos", "[", "Pi", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"sin", " ", "of", " ", "\[Pi]"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "4", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Sqrt", " ", "of", " ", "4"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976625167095028*^9, 3.9766252492925262`*^9}, {
   3.976625427460882*^9, 3.9766254395536823`*^9}, {3.976625508033922*^9, 
   3.976625691710966*^9}, 3.976626016406105*^9, {3.9766260981979046`*^9, 
   3.9766263113909817`*^9}, {3.9766264375973015`*^9, 3.976626439270464*^9}, {
   3.976898321733656*^9, 
   3.9768983224933662`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a5e3cadb-2b53-3e49-9b99-\
769ed5061123"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "However, even basic functions have some nuances. For example, Mathematica \
always assumes that the input is in Radians instead of degrees. One way to \
remedy this is to use the Degree constant which is just equal to ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   FractionBox["\[Pi]", "180"], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "540b8d0b-4e77-2a44-aa00-4ac048a88c4e"],
 ". Using this appropriately will switch between degrees and radians:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.97662634550893*^9, 3.976626413804716*^9}, {
  3.9766264602760944`*^9, 
  3.9766264728554325`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"de360028-5631-854b-bc22-\
8afc2fb24b58"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Sin", "[", 
   RowBox[{"45", " ", "Degree"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Sin", " ", "of", " ", 
    SuperscriptBox["45", 
     TemplateBox[<|
      "boxes" -> FormBox["\[EmptySmallCircle]", TraditionalForm], 
       "errors" -> {}, "input" -> "\\circ", "state" -> "Boxes"|>,
      "TeXAssistantTemplate"]]}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "45", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Sin", " ", "of", " ", "45", " ", "Radians"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.97662634550893*^9, 3.9766264338919067`*^9}, {
  3.976626477859991*^9, 3.976626484909809*^9}, {3.976626578669834*^9, 
  3.976626611878683*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[8]:=",ExpressionUUID->"1361c55b-03fd-1345-ba44-3757b35f820b"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "You may have also noticed that the output above is exact, meaning there are \
no decimal approximations. This is because Mathematica will always try to \
give an exact solution unless told to do a numerical approximation. This can \
be helpful since Mathematica will also try to simplify symbolic expressions. \
However, when dealing with actual data you will likely want actual numerical \
values. This can be remedied using the ",
 StyleBox["N[] ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "command.  This command will default to storing as many digits as possible, \
but you can also tell Mathematica to only keep a certain number of digits by \
adding a parameter. Note that using ",
 StyleBox["N[]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " without extra parameters will not necessarily output all of the stored \
digits. You can show all the digits by selected the output cell and clicking \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]show all digits\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.976626766536146*^9}, {
  3.9766269487234592`*^9, 3.976627242394411*^9}, {3.976627331328882*^9, 
  3.9766273550590134`*^9}, {3.9766274486607075`*^9, 3.976627506459364*^9}, {
  3.976627587423706*^9, 
  3.976627617290825*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"a4e277a1-f616-6845-97d0-\
705b82e767ac"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"N", "[", 
   RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
    "numerical", " ", "value", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", "square", " ", 
     "root", " ", "of", " ", "2"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{
    "Mathematica", " ", "will", " ", "only", " ", "output", " ", "6", " ", 
     "digits"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{
    "but", " ", "actually", " ", "has", " ", "evaluated", " ", "a", " ", 
     "lot", " ", "more", " ", "digits"}]}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"N", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}], ",", "3"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
    "numerical", " ", "value", " ", "of", " ", "square", " ", "root", " ", 
     "of", " ", "2", " ", "up", " ", "to", " ", "3", " ", "digits"}], ",", 
    " ", 
    RowBox[{
    "mathematica", " ", "will", " ", "both", " ", "output", " ", "and", " ", 
     "store", " ", "the", " ", "exact", " ", "value"}]}], "*)"}], 
  "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"N", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "2", "]"}], ",", "10"}], "]"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "numerical", " ", "value", " ", "of", " ", "square", " ", "root", " ", 
    "of", " ", "2", " ", "up", " ", "to", " ", "10", " ", "digits"}], 
   "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.976626766536146*^9}, {
  3.9766269487234592`*^9, 3.976627242394411*^9}, {3.976627331328882*^9, 
  3.97662743672867*^9}, {3.976627512816534*^9, 3.9766275763355885`*^9}, {
  3.976627620787407*^9, 
  3.976627631683466*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"cddc2cf5-83c8-3144-a7e2-\
f5fd447261a5"],

Cell["\<\
Note also that once a decimal approximation is calculated, using it in any \
other calculation will result in Mathematica giving a decimal approximation:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.976626766536146*^9}, {
  3.9766269487234592`*^9, 3.976627242394411*^9}, {3.976627331328882*^9, 
  3.976627354560049*^9}, {3.976627644377527*^9, 
  3.97662769077693*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"80665c4a-4386-ef4a-9e70-\
f1e87001e2af"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"var", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"N", "[", "Pi", "]"}]}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"numerical", " ", "value", " ", "of", " ", "\[Pi]"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"2", "*", " ", "var"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "gives", " ", "numerical", " ", "value", " ", "of", " ", "2", " ", 
    "\[Pi]"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"2", " ", "*", " ", "Pi", " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "gives", " ", "exact", " ", "expression", " ", "for", " ", "2", " ", 
    "\[Pi]"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.976626766536146*^9}, {
  3.9766269487234592`*^9, 3.976627242394411*^9}, {3.976627331328882*^9, 
  3.976627354560049*^9}, {3.976627644377527*^9, 
  3.9766277709060707`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0dcb6a75-c988-d141-a161-\
4e4d067d1815"],

Cell["\<\
As a final note, you can clear variable values using the Clear[] command, and \
doing Clear[\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]`*\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote]], will clear \
all variables in the notebook. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976898724423889*^9, 
  3.976898772478348*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6c273c52-5955-8740-b4ed-\
f5bc5a5bccac"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Clear", "[", "var", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"clears", " ", "var", " ", "from", " ", "memory"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Clear", "[", "\"\<`*\>\"", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "Clears", " ", "all", " ", "variables", " ", "from", " ", "memory"}], 
   "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976898724423889*^9, 3.976898745997261*^9}, {
  3.976898776599861*^9, 3.976898776790079*^9}, {3.976898862920908*^9, 
  3.976898879397829*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bae585b3-411e-4940-89d7-\
abf0a74fa448"],

Cell["Now, let\[CloseCurlyQuote]s let you put some of this to use with an \
exercise.", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.976626766536146*^9}, {
  3.9766269487234592`*^9, 3.976627242394411*^9}, {3.976627331328882*^9, 
  3.976627354560049*^9}, {3.976627644377527*^9, 3.976627690131283*^9}, {
  3.9766277919699287`*^9, 3.97662782573975*^9}, {3.9936464722195377`*^9, 
  3.993646477420182*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0fd14116-d303-9a40-9ac6-\
124923266b2c"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Exercise", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.976626766536146*^9}, {
  3.9766269487234592`*^9, 3.976627242394411*^9}, {3.976627331328882*^9, 
  3.976627354560049*^9}, {3.976627644377527*^9, 3.976627690131283*^9}, {
  3.9766277919699287`*^9, 3.97662782573975*^9}, {3.9936464722195377`*^9, 
  3.9936464994634323`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0ff25fcf-d8ae-41d8-af7a-\
8b8276cf3e35"],

Cell[TextData[{
 " The ",
 StyleBox["Log[]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 " command for logarithms also defaults to the natural log, and you can \
either use the change-of-base formula, or a Mathematica command. Try to see \
if you can calculate ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SubscriptBox["Log", "2"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "ec1e1aff-c903-4c64-b89c-607f11508f8c"],
 "(2365) below to 5 digits, don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t forget to look at the \
documentation (F1) if you are unsure what to do."
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.976626766536146*^9}, {
  3.9766269487234592`*^9, 3.976627242394411*^9}, {3.976627331328882*^9, 
  3.976627354560049*^9}, {3.976627644377527*^9, 3.976627690131283*^9}, {
  3.9766277919699287`*^9, 3.97662782573975*^9}, {3.9936464722195377`*^9, 
  3.993646475887508*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"5cd6d053-3b1d-4ab0-9a31-\
b7bf4e52e725"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"(*", 
  RowBox[{"Your", " ", "code", " ", "here"}], "*)"}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 
  3.9766267695644684`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2088cfbf-f691-6148-afee-\
2c0dab708bcb"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Solution", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 
  3.9766267914184475`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"62118b4b-2216-6140-b13a-\
b4c4b42eaf55"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "The documentation indicates that the log command requires an extra input if \
I want to change the base Log[",
 StyleBox["base,value",
  FontSlant->"Italic"],
 "], and then we can use ",
 StyleBox["N ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "to give 3 digits. You can either do this in multiple command lines:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.9766269130588646`*^9}, {
   3.976627259320633*^9, 3.976627299779793*^9}, 
   3.9766278564816456`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"80bfab3f-9e76-8b41-890c-\
d5633bed3369"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"Log", "[", 
    RowBox[{"2", ",", "2365"}], "]"}], " ", ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    SubscriptBox["Log", "2"], 
    RowBox[{"(", "2365", ")"}]}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"N", "[", 
   RowBox[{"%", ",", "3"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "get", " ", "three", " ", "digits", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", "previous",
     " ", "output"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766266483431053`*^9, 3.9766267892216873`*^9}, {
  3.9766268203217144`*^9, 3.9766268273677673`*^9}, {3.9766269536122246`*^9, 
  3.9766269547075787`*^9}, {3.9766278300595703`*^9, 
  3.9766279286321144`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"73faf163-9f62-934f-adda-\
4367a6e35d14"],

Cell["Or in one command line:", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976626928136223*^9, 3.9766269303998184`*^9}, {
   3.976627302224188*^9, 3.976627305857519*^9}, 
   3.976627844597479*^9},ExpressionUUID->"807d6c83-b2cd-f94e-8a9b-\
485ff9be5fbc"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"N", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Log", "[", 
     RowBox[{"2", ",", "2365"}], "]"}], ",", "3"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"get", " ", "three", " ", "digits", " ", "of", " ", 
    SubscriptBox["Log", "2"], 
    RowBox[{"(", "2365", ")"}]}], "*)"}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976626928136223*^9, 3.9766269303998184`*^9}, {
  3.976627302224188*^9, 3.976627305857519*^9}, {3.976627844979641*^9, 
  3.976627864830118*^9}, {3.9766278964839096`*^9, 3.976627918086195*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[38]:=",ExpressionUUID->"f7f763e9-264f-c146-9738-2b695db60bff"]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Lists, Vectors, and Matrices", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365436435215*^9, 3.976365455965885*^9}, {
   3.976365494172184*^9, 3.9763655874665375`*^9}, {3.976366064886591*^9, 
   3.976366125368452*^9}, 3.976623793298382*^9, {3.976624746177988*^9, 
   3.9766247566030235`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6e248035-dfa8-ed40-9744-\
f6685cffdd0e"],

Cell["\<\
Mathematica can also define lists using  curly braces {} where each element \
is separated by a comma,\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365436435215*^9, 3.976365455965885*^9}, {
   3.976365494172184*^9, 3.9763655874665375`*^9}, {3.976366064886591*^9, 
   3.976366125368452*^9}, 
   3.976623793298382*^9},ExpressionUUID->"ecfb96f0-ae44-8848-be1e-\
20c12186833b"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"list", " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{"{", 
   RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "3", ",", "4", ",", "5", ",", "6", ",", "7"}], 
   "}"}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365436435215*^9, 3.976365455965885*^9}, {
  3.976365494172184*^9, 3.976365583407854*^9}, {3.9763659473731384`*^9, 
  3.9763659487522545`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[28]:=",ExpressionUUID->"752e32f2-ac0b-1f4f-ad9d-5e9b25b05db1"],

Cell["\<\
You can access the elements of a list using double square braces [[#]], where \
# is the position you wish to access. note that the list begins indexing at \
1. Using the index -1 will give the last item in the list, you can also get \
sublists by using ;;. For example list[[2;;]] will return a sublist beginning \
from the second element until the last element:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365599330433*^9, 3.976365865198591*^9}, {
  3.976365934401325*^9, 
  3.9763659352602196`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"daf8e0ee-125e-7640-b2c3-\
40a856374681"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"list", "[", 
   RowBox[{"[", "1", "]"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "returns", " ", "the", " ", "item", " ", "in", " ", "the", " ", "first", " ",
     "position"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"list", "[", 
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{"-", "1"}], "]"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "returns", " ", "the", " ", "item", " ", "in", " ", "the", " ", "last", " ",
     "position"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"list", "[", 
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{"2", ";;"}], "]"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "returns", " ", "a", " ", "sublist", " ", "excluding", " ", "the", " ", 
    "first", " ", "element", " ", "in", " ", "the", " ", "list"}], 
   "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365599330433*^9, 3.9763656866494713`*^9}, {
   3.976365721089281*^9, 3.976365774630724*^9}, 3.976365828092552*^9, {
   3.9763658673222885`*^9, 3.976365876117693*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[29]:=",ExpressionUUID->"cf8077f2-616f-5043-a2c7-716a4145917a"],

Cell["\<\
You can also define a nested list, and you will then have to use two \
different indices to determine which element you want to access.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365976810837*^9, 3.9763659941984825`*^9}, {
   3.976628014181612*^9, 3.976628017011959*^9}, {3.9768944465345936`*^9, 
   3.9768944620079594`*^9}, {3.9768945797159405`*^9, 3.976894591632183*^9}, {
   3.976894627972193*^9, 3.976894730656557*^9}, {3.9768948083395767`*^9, 
   3.976894925921831*^9}, 3.9768950136047993`*^9, {3.9768950479679604`*^9, 
   3.9768951215668297`*^9}, {3.9768961889629593`*^9, 
   3.97689622109449*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1cb7e17c-76b5-0a45-9019-\
988599b9af03"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"nestedList", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "3"}], "}"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"4", ",", "5", ",", "6"}], "}"}]}], "}"}]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"nestedList", "[", 
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "3"}], "]"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{
    "returns", " ", "the", " ", "third", " ", "element", " ", "in", " ", 
     "the", " ", "first", " ", "list"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"the", " ", "number", " ", "3"}]}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"nestedList", "[", 
   RowBox[{"[", "1", "]"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"returns", " ", "the", " ", "entire", " ", "first", " ", "list"}], 
   "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"nestedList", "[", 
   RowBox[{"[", 
    RowBox[{";;", ",", "1"}], "]"}], "]"}], "  ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "returns", " ", "then", " ", "first", " ", "element", " ", "of", " ", 
    "each", " ", "list"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365976810837*^9, 3.9763659941984825`*^9}, {
   3.976628014181612*^9, 3.976628017011959*^9}, {3.9768944465345936`*^9, 
   3.9768944620079594`*^9}, {3.9768945797159405`*^9, 3.976894591632183*^9}, {
   3.976894627972193*^9, 3.976894730656557*^9}, {3.9768948083395767`*^9, 
   3.976894925921831*^9}, 3.9768950136047993`*^9, {3.9768950479679604`*^9, 
   3.9768951215668297`*^9}, {3.9768961889629593`*^9, 3.976896333050375*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[48]:=",ExpressionUUID->"27fe3d1c-233f-404e-8bf8-4ddb5e7dd81c"],

Cell["\<\
Similar to other variables, you can also perform operations on lists of the \
same length. You can apply the same operation on all elements of the list at \
once\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365976810837*^9, 3.9763659941984825`*^9}, {
   3.976628014181612*^9, 3.976628017011959*^9}, {3.9768944465345936`*^9, 
   3.9768944620079594`*^9}, {3.9768945797159405`*^9, 3.976894591632183*^9}, {
   3.976894627972193*^9, 3.976894730656557*^9}, {3.9768948083395767`*^9, 
   3.976894925921831*^9}, 3.9768950136047993`*^9, {3.9768950479679604`*^9, 
   3.9768951215668297`*^9}, {3.9768961889629593`*^9, 
   3.9768962208252335`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"31af1748-e32d-8d47-9d07-\
2e8fc706a341"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "lists"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"listA", " ", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "3", ",", "4"}], "}"}]}], " ", ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"listB", "=", " ", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{
       RowBox[{"-", "2"}], ",", "4", ",", 
       RowBox[{"-", "6"}], ",", "8"}], "}"}]}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"(*", 
    RowBox[{"do", " ", "elementwise", " ", "operations"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"listA", " ", "+", " ", "listB"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"listA", " ", "*", " ", "listB"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"(*", 
    RowBox[{
    "multiply", " ", "each", " ", "element", " ", "on", " ", "the", " ", 
     "list", " ", "by", " ", "2"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"2", "*", " ", "listA"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"(*", 
    RowBox[{
    "subtract", " ", "2", " ", "from", " ", "each", " ", "element", " ", "of",
      " ", "the", " ", "list"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"listA", " ", "-", " ", "2"}]}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365976810837*^9, 3.9763659941984825`*^9}, {
  3.976628014181612*^9, 3.976628017011959*^9}, {3.9768944465345936`*^9, 
  3.9768944620079594`*^9}, {3.9768945797159405`*^9, 3.976894591632183*^9}, {
  3.976894627972193*^9, 3.976894730656557*^9}, {3.9768948083395767`*^9, 
  3.976895083266512*^9}, {3.976895123172323*^9, 3.9768951426816216`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[30]:=",ExpressionUUID->"269de13b-0b2f-7342-9d28-6a98d0cbd025"],

Cell["\<\
In general, using a function on a list will apply that function on each \
element of a list:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365976810837*^9, 3.9763659941984825`*^9}, {
  3.976628014181612*^9, 3.976628017011959*^9}, {3.9768944465345936`*^9, 
  3.9768944609282856`*^9}, {3.9768951518010464`*^9, 3.9768951926360455`*^9}, {
  3.976895237547014*^9, 3.9768953303716164`*^9}, {3.9768953803725433`*^9, 
  3.976895382880556*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1d563033-10b6-ca4d-a22a-\
01147b0b5a04"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"list", " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "3"}], "}"}]}], ";"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "list"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"Sqrt", "[", "list", "]"}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976365976810837*^9, 3.9763659941984825`*^9}, {
  3.976628014181612*^9, 3.976628017011959*^9}, {3.9768944465345936`*^9, 
  3.9768944609282856`*^9}, {3.9768951518010464`*^9, 3.9768951926360455`*^9}, {
  3.976895237547014*^9, 3.9768953478727074`*^9}, {3.976898679022768*^9, 
  3.976898691739668*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1e220b15-208d-5a42-a198-\
7255075fe913"],

Cell["\<\
There are some functions which are designed to work with lists. For example, \
passing a list to the Sort function will output the sorted list:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976895362876238*^9, 3.9768954080357304`*^9}, {
  3.9768954564567585`*^9, 3.9768954686449223`*^9}, {3.9768955184795704`*^9, 
  3.9768955439615974`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"b027195e-4b58-3843-b0ae-\
cee91b86421d"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"myList", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{
    "3", ",", "8", ",", "9", ",", "10", ",", "3", ",", "5", ",", "1", ",", 
     "2"}], "}"}]}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "a", " ", "list"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Sort", "[", "myList", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"sort", " ", "list"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976895362876238*^9, 3.9768954080357304`*^9}, {
  3.9768954564567585`*^9, 3.9768955145351276`*^9}, {3.9768956414210033`*^9, 
  3.9768956427251415`*^9}, {3.9768965136013756`*^9, 3.9768965146462994`*^9}, {
  3.9768986665078163`*^9, 
  3.9768986774730225`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"2ae3157a-1d91-2347-81a6-\
dbc050e05a08"],

Cell["\<\
Other useful commands are things like the Total[], Mean[], and \
StandardDeviation[] commands. We will go over these kinds of operations more \
in section V.

Lists can also work as vectors, and you can calculate the standard dot \
product by either using the Dot[] command or simply using a period as a \
multiplication symbol:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768955461929264`*^9, 3.976895584835163*^9}, {
  3.9768956170233192`*^9, 3.9768956988848476`*^9}, {3.9768957600170784`*^9, 
  3.976895944909956*^9}, {3.9768965011180763`*^9, 
  3.976896505610016*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"dc194367-8a6a-2b45-982d-\
41b0acc45f17"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"A", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", "1", ",", "1"}], "}"}]}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "vectors"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"B", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"{", 
    RowBox[{"1", ",", 
     RowBox[{"-", "1"}], ",", "1"}], "}"}]}], " "}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"A", ".", "B", " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"calculate", " ", "dot", " ", "product"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768955461929264`*^9, 3.976895584835163*^9}, {
  3.9768956170233192`*^9, 3.9768956988848476`*^9}, {3.9768957600170784`*^9, 
  3.976895797583748*^9}, {3.9768959485191326`*^9, 
  3.976896027629135*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"3b116fd6-03c7-8848-a9c1-\
804e5f0598aa"],

Cell["\<\
You can also define matrices using nested lists, and you can perform matrix \
multiplication again using the Dot[] command. You can also ask Mathematica to \
display lists and nested lists as column vectors and matrices using the \
MatrixForm[] command. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768960164754696`*^9, 3.9768960209229527`*^9}, {
  3.9768961204113693`*^9, 3.976896179862047*^9}, {3.976896359120861*^9, 
  3.9768964865718613`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0f17a9ad-9a30-4d44-b531-\
2c91bb745d31"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"M", " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"0", ",", "1"}], "}"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", "0"}], "}"}]}], "}"}]}], ";"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "the", " ", "matrix"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"v", " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", "0"}], "}"}]}], ";"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "a", " ", "vector"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "display", " ", "M", " ", "as", " ", "a", " ", "matrix", " ", "and", " ", 
    "v", " ", "as", " ", "a", " ", "column", " ", "vector"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"MatrixForm", "[", "M", "]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"MatrixForm", "[", "v", "]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"MatrixForm", "[", 
   RowBox[{"M", ".", "M"}], " ", "]"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"multiply", " ", "the", " ", "matrix", " ", "by", " ", "itself"}], 
   "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"MatrixForm", "[", 
   RowBox[{"M", ".", "v"}], "]"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "Apply", " ", "the", " ", "matrix", " ", "M", " ", "to", " ", "the", " ", 
    "vector", " ", "A"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768960164754696`*^9, 3.9768960209229527`*^9}, {
  3.9768961204113693`*^9, 3.97689618023361*^9}, {3.9768963508485317`*^9, 
  3.976896356148262*^9}, {3.976896410999939*^9, 3.976896429640648*^9}, {
  3.9768965196910744`*^9, 3.9768966549328957`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[76]:=",ExpressionUUID->"3de8e066-44cd-834a-beaf-a9ab01310dd6"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Note that using the MatrixForm command turns your list into something else. \
Therefore, if you try to define a variable using MatrixForm,",
 StyleBox[" it will prevent you from performing operations on the matrix:",
  FontWeight->"Bold"]
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768967012513695`*^9, 
  3.976896781435976*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e724cf59-b556-cc48-9631-\
7371d733a569"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"notAMatrix", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"MatrixForm", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", "0"}], "}"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"0", ",", "1"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], "]"}]}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "stores", " ", "the", " ", "MatrixForm", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", 
    "matrix"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"notAVector", " ", "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{"MatrixForm", "[", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"1", ",", "0"}], "}"}], "]"}]}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "stores", " ", "the", " ", "MatrixForm", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", 
    "vector"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{"notAMatrix", ".", "notAVector", " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"doesn", "'"}], "t", " ", "do", " ", "the", " ", "actual", " ", 
    "calculation"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768967012513695`*^9, 
  3.976896920065464*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"bcee7df9-9ad8-3d4d-823f-\
cbabb4af0fa4"],

Cell["\<\
Mathematica can also do a number of matrix calculations such as row \
reduction, eigenvalue and eigenvector calculations, determinants, inverses, \
etc.:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768969380038223`*^9, 3.9768969900221176`*^9}, {
  3.9768970383891506`*^9, 3.9768970388117065`*^9}, {3.976897074746334*^9, 
  3.976897085616146*^9}, {3.976897233917818*^9, 
  3.976897240871063*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"7cfcc571-79af-884d-9b53-\
230e909639cf"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"mat", " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", "2", ",", "3", ",", "4"}], "}"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"5", ",", "6", ",", "7", ",", "8"}], "}"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"9", ",", "10", ",", "11", ",", "12"}], "}"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"13", ",", "14", ",", "15", ",", "16"}], "}"}]}], "}"}]}], 
   ";"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"a", " ", "matrix"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Det", "[", "mat", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"calculate", " ", "the", " ", "determinant"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"NullSpace", "[", "mat", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "returns", " ", "the", " ", "vectors", " ", "which", " ", "span", " ", 
    "the", " ", "null", " ", "space", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", "matrix"}], 
   "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768969380038223`*^9, 3.9768970892949104`*^9}, {
  3.976897157616337*^9, 
  3.9768972826719265`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"97ae1148-e583-864f-a2ad-\
74b474f28237"],

Cell["We will end this section with an exercise.", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768972893233166`*^9, 3.976897416595579*^9}, 
   3.9768975287018185`*^9, {3.9768977344101334`*^9, 3.9768978208786297`*^9}, {
   3.9768985471115074`*^9, 3.976898553525612*^9}, {3.976898944904356*^9, 
   3.9768989473018093`*^9}, {3.976899037941679*^9, 3.976899038165312*^9}, {
   3.993646422646864*^9, 
   3.9936464326326227`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"fc7d8bd9-7934-1949-bb98-\
ddba02f0210e"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Exercise", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768972893233166`*^9, 3.976897416595579*^9}, 
   3.9768975287018185`*^9, {3.9768977344101334`*^9, 3.9768978208786297`*^9}, {
   3.9768985471115074`*^9, 3.976898553525612*^9}, {3.976898944904356*^9, 
   3.9768989473018093`*^9}, {3.976899037941679*^9, 3.976899038165312*^9}, {
   3.993646422646864*^9, 
   3.9936464419869347`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"82b83fd2-d0b2-4ead-9176-\
db799ae3c3be"],

Cell["\<\
 In the Input cell below, I have defined an example matrix, H. Use the \
Mathematica documentation to find the eigenvalues, eigenvectors, and an \
orthogonal basis for the eigenspace (you may find the commands Eigenvalues[], \
Eigenvectors[], Eigensystem[], and Orthogonalize[]).\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768972893233166`*^9, 3.976897416595579*^9}, 
   3.9768975287018185`*^9, {3.9768977344101334`*^9, 3.9768978208786297`*^9}, {
   3.9768985471115074`*^9, 3.976898553525612*^9}, {3.976898944904356*^9, 
   3.9768989473018093`*^9}, {3.976899037941679*^9, 3.976899038165312*^9}, 
   3.993646422646864*^9},ExpressionUUID->"b754c6bb-9d5e-4892-9395-\
78ffca698891"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"H", "=", 
   RowBox[{"N", "[", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"1", ",", "1", ",", "2"}], "}"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{
        RowBox[{"-", "1"}], ",", "5", ",", "2"}], "}"}], ",", 
      RowBox[{"{", 
       RowBox[{"2", ",", 
        RowBox[{"-", "1"}], ",", "4"}], "}"}]}], "}"}], "]"}]}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"H", " ", "matrix"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"your", " ", "code", " ", "here"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768972893233166`*^9, 3.976897417374563*^9}, {
  3.976897536545912*^9, 3.9768975771364403`*^9}, {3.976897645438492*^9, 
  3.976897758285425*^9}, {3.9768985561636677`*^9, 3.97689856688221*^9}, {
  3.9768990440742435`*^9, 3.9768990461894016`*^9}, {3.9768990857954407`*^9, 
  3.976899102917898*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[20]:=",ExpressionUUID->"ebafc7b3-9a78-1d46-b46e-e1d28fede8f4"]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Solution", "Subsubsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976897763011711*^9, 3.9768977651895523`*^9}, 
   3.9768984866973057`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"a62c5c44-0c6b-ab42-b039-\
c07356fa2982"],

Cell["\<\
There are multiple ways to do this, but here is one possibility:
The eigensystem command will return both the eigenvalues and the associated \
eigenvectors:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976897763011711*^9, 3.9768977651895523`*^9}, {
  3.9768984889033146`*^9, 3.9768985020727196`*^9}, {3.9768989714489975`*^9, 
  3.976898981202057*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"1aa3708d-7403-e348-9ab8-\
d39a86f8680c"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"eigenSolution", " ", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Eigensystem", "[", "H", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "find", " ", "the", " ", "eigenvectors", " ", "and", " ", "eigenvalues"}], 
   "*)"}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976897763011711*^9, 3.9768977892487164`*^9}, {
  3.9768984689318886`*^9, 3.976898611639147*^9}, {3.976898896271799*^9, 
  3.976898908415104*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[21]:=",ExpressionUUID->"0adf9df8-c37e-984c-b627-92b34f34774a"],

Cell["\<\
To find an orthogonal basis, I can use the Orthogonalize command on the 2nd \
list of eigenSolution\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768989177847786`*^9, 
  3.976898967697918*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"0b4ecd64-ad3a-8148-9b90-\
51b4ae96b9e8"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "=", " ", 
  RowBox[{"Orthogonalize", "[", 
   RowBox[{"eigenSolution", "[", 
    RowBox[{"[", "2", "]"}], "]"}], "]"}], " "}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768989177847786`*^9, 3.9768990319507866`*^9}, {
  3.976899112963785*^9, 3.9768991242908974`*^9}, {3.992946223372526*^9, 
  3.9929463671901207`*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[27]:=",ExpressionUUID->"9fac8db7-c6ac-064d-b4a7-fa8da8e91c6e"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "To check to make sure they are orthogonal, we can calculate their inner \
products. Notice that the not all inner products are not exactly zero, this \
is due to the roundoff error that occurs during the numerical calculation. \
However, the numerical outputs are on the order of ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   SuperscriptBox["10", 
    RowBox[{"-", "17"}]], TraditionalForm]],
  FormatType->TraditionalForm,ExpressionUUID->
  "12682eea-c75b-fb4e-b240-1c130624086b"],
 ", which is basically zero. The orthogonalize command also returns \
normalized vectors"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9929463455739994`*^9, 3.992946351176609*^9}, {
  3.9929463888569584`*^9, 3.9929464591240215`*^9}, {3.99294649046706*^9, 
  3.992946576439539*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d5166785-2110-9b42-827b-\
818054ca53f7"],

Cell[BoxData[
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "calculate", " ", "the", " ", "inner", " ", "product", " ", "to", " ", 
    "show", " ", "the", " ", "vectors", " ", "are", " ", "orthogonal"}], 
   "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"[", "1", "]"}], "]"}], ".", 
    RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", 
     RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "[", 
      RowBox[{"[", "2", "]"}], "]"}], "]"}]}], " ", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"[", "1", "]"}], "]"}], ".", 
    RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", 
     RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "[", 
      RowBox[{"[", "3", "]"}], "]"}], "]"}]}], " ", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "[", 
     RowBox[{"[", "3", "]"}], "]"}], ".", 
    RowBox[{"Conjugate", "[", 
     RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "[", 
      RowBox[{"[", "2", "]"}], "]"}], "]"}]}], " ", "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"(*", 
    RowBox[{
    "the", " ", "resulting", " ", "vectors", " ", "are", " ", "also", " ", 
     "orthonormal"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
   RowBox[{"Table", "[", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"Norm", "[", 
      RowBox[{"orthogonalVectors", "[", 
       RowBox[{"[", "j", "]"}], "]"}], "]"}], ",", 
     RowBox[{"{", 
      RowBox[{"j", ",", "1", ",", "3"}], "}"}]}], "]"}]}]}]], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9768989177847786`*^9, 3.9768990319507866`*^9}, {
  3.976899112963785*^9, 3.9768991242908974`*^9}, {3.992946223372526*^9, 
  3.9929463404804*^9}, {3.992946370866171*^9, 3.9929463875277653`*^9}, {
  3.9929464647142334`*^9, 3.992946482563589*^9}, {3.9929465809820824`*^9, 
  3.992946667521635*^9}},
 CellLabel->"In[38]:=",ExpressionUUID->"b917857e-1d24-de4d-b6b3-8e70ae35aafb"]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]]
}, Closed]],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["II. Functions and Numerics", "Section",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766254434669495`*^9, 3.976625451874857*^9}, {
  3.9766254849520435`*^9, 3.9766254926092052`*^9}, {3.9768992048074665`*^9, 
  3.976899211327976*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"d3a250f6-a55b-f64b-8f46-\
547a911b33da"],

Cell["\<\
This section covers how to define and evaluate functions in Mathematica as \
well as some nuances of the numerical calculations and units in Mathematica. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766254434669495`*^9, 3.976625451874857*^9}, {
  3.9766254849520435`*^9, 3.9766254926092052`*^9}, {3.9768992048074665`*^9, 
  3.9768993275938263`*^9}, {3.977248737153721*^9, 3.977248738693657*^9}, {
  3.9775032145745144`*^9, 
  3.9775032156780834`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"6ec21fd4-8777-d74e-9c26-\
516e2edbbd1a"],

Cell[CellGroupData[{

Cell["Function Definition", "Subsection",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766254434669495`*^9, 3.976625451874857*^9}, {
   3.9766254849520435`*^9, 3.9766254926092052`*^9}, {3.9768992078334007`*^9, 
   3.9768992093788223`*^9}, 3.9769678825932713`*^9, {3.9772487412112255`*^9, 
   3.9772487431668816`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"52b70582-8941-5b45-b6da-\
3aee9d403f00"],

Cell["\<\
As discussed in the previous section, Mathematica has a wide variety of \
pre-built functions and commands that you can use to do all sorts of \
calculations. While we will introduce you to some useful pre-built functions \
throughout this guide, anything you will ever need to know how to use \
pre-built functions can be found in the documentation or through an online \
search.

Our focus in this section is how to define your own functions in Mathematica. \
The syntax for defining a function in Mathematica is similar to that of \
defining variables:\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766254434669495`*^9, 3.976625451874857*^9}, {
  3.9766254849520435`*^9, 3.9766254926092052`*^9}, {3.9768992078334007`*^9, 
  3.9768992093788223`*^9}, {3.9769678853382244`*^9, 3.976967914747629*^9}, {
  3.9769679589026985`*^9, 3.97696811767338*^9}, {3.97696823440654*^9, 
  3.9769683603095226`*^9}, {3.9769683951411457`*^9, 
  3.9769684864755154`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"fc7d9cb2-87c0-3a49-9aaa-\
0e0e6bf4ff18"],

Cell[TextData[StyleBox["Function[var1_, var2_, ...] = <your function here> ",
 FontWeight->"Bold"]], "Text",
 InitializationCell->True,
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766254434669495`*^9, 3.976625451874857*^9}, {
  3.9766254849520435`*^9, 3.9766254926092052`*^9}, {3.9768992078334007`*^9, 
  3.9768992093788223`*^9}, {3.9769678853382244`*^9, 3.976967914747629*^9}, {
  3.9769679589026985`*^9, 3.97696811767338*^9}, {3.97696823440654*^9, 
  3.9769683603095226`*^9}, {3.9769683951411457`*^9, 
  3.976968579471592*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"91633c2b-c57a-174d-8972-\
a17585896e40"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Notice that for each variable (var#) must have an underscore after it if \
you want Mathematica to recognize it as a function variable. \n",
 StyleBox["\n",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "Once you have defined a function this way, you can call it like you would \
any other function:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766254434669495`*^9, 3.976625451874857*^9}, {
  3.9766254849520435`*^9, 3.9766254926092052`*^9}, {3.9768992078334007`*^9, 
  3.9768992093788223`*^9}, {3.9769678853382244`*^9, 3.976967914747629*^9}, {
  3.9769679589026985`*^9, 3.97696811767338*^9}, {3.97696823440654*^9, 
  3.9769683603095226`*^9}, {3.9769683951411457`*^9, 3.9769684697876816`*^9}, {
  3.9769685642815495`*^9, 
  3.9769686211153927`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"daf3b6a9-4902-4b41-bfcb-\
a65553d8fe4e"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"f", "[", 
    RowBox[{"x_", ",", "y_"}], "]"}], "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["x", "2"], " ", "+", 
    SuperscriptBox["y", "2"]}]}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Define", " ", "the", " ", "function"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"f", "[", 
   RowBox[{"2", ",", "0"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"returns", " ", "f", 
    RowBox[{"(", 
     RowBox[{"2", ",", "0"}], ")"}]}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"f", "[", 
   RowBox[{"w", ",", "z"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "will", " ", "return", " ", "the", " ", "function", " ", "in", " ", 
    "terms", " ", "of", " ", "w", " ", "and", " ", "z"}], "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9766254434669495`*^9, 3.976625451874857*^9}, {
  3.9766254849520435`*^9, 3.9766254926092052`*^9}, {3.9768992078334007`*^9, 
  3.976899209864382*^9}, {3.9769683261892147`*^9, 3.9769683289061394`*^9}, {
  3.9769683887685013`*^9, 3.9769683896123753`*^9}, {3.9769686235758266`*^9, 
  3.976968694113144*^9}, {3.9769691850878315`*^9, 3.976969197020708*^9}},
 CellLabel->
  "In[137]:=",ExpressionUUID->"00722c8a-be16-5a4f-becb-14a5f604b4c8"],

Cell["You can even use functions in other function definitions:", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976968800388624*^9, 3.976968847502554*^9}, {
  3.9769688850077553`*^9, 3.9769690397392616`*^9}, {3.976970548823578*^9, 
  3.976970593035124*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"f044e200-ad2e-c446-9c51-\
d8b7b6eeeca0"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Clear", "[", "f", "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Clear", " ", "the", " ", "function", " ", "f"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"f", "[", "x_", "]"}], "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Cos", "[", "x", "]"}], 
    RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "x", "]"}]}]}], " ", "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"g", "[", "x_", "]"}], "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    SuperscriptBox["x", "2"], 
    RowBox[{"f", "[", "x", "]"}]}]}], " ", 
  "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976968800388624*^9, 3.976968847502554*^9}, {
  3.9769688850077553`*^9, 3.9769690397392616`*^9}, {3.976970548823578*^9, 
  3.9769706332083683`*^9}, {3.9769707774990883`*^9, 3.9769708627428627`*^9}},
 CellLabel->
  "In[172]:=",ExpressionUUID->"21b1e7ab-ffec-5947-b38e-6db427e4bf61"],

Cell["\<\
Notice also that when multiplying variables, I do not need to use * symbol. \
If I simply put a space between two symbols, Mathematica will understand that \
I want to multiply them. \
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9769708522428417`*^9, 
  3.976970911844551*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"82cc5436-1f85-4340-9a25-\
4274b1bb5839"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Functions defined have some useful built-in properties. For example, the \
derivative command ",
 StyleBox["D[]",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 ", has a shortcut for single variable functions:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976968800388624*^9, 3.976968847502554*^9}, {
  3.9769688850077553`*^9, 3.9769690397392616`*^9}, {3.976970548823578*^9, 
  3.9769705922315044`*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"ee5767ab-38ce-5a4e-8b46-\
c930fc0c1ddd"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Clear", "[", 
   RowBox[{"f", ",", "g"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"clear", " ", "previous", " ", "function", " ", "definition"}], 
   "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"g", "[", "x_", "]"}], "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Exp", "[", "x", "]"}], 
    RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "x", "]"}]}]}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "a", " ", "function"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"D", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"g", "[", "x", "]"}], ",", "x"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "calculate", " ", "the", " ", "first", " ", "derivative", " ", "of", " ", 
    "the", " ", "function"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"g", "'"}], "[", "x", "]"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "Another", " ", "way", " ", "to", " ", "claculate", " ", "the", " ", 
    "first", " ", "derivative", " ", "of", " ", "the", " ", "function"}], 
   "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.976968800388624*^9, 3.976968847502554*^9}, {
  3.9769688850077553`*^9, 3.9769691803324356`*^9}, {3.976970783952322*^9, 
  3.9769708252759113`*^9}},
 CellLabel->
  "In[175]:=",ExpressionUUID->"2c2bd127-a1d7-7940-93db-98b0a321d1a6"],

Cell["\<\
You can also define vector functions and perform various differential \
operators on both scalar and vector functions. Mathematica can also handle \
differential operators in different coordinate systems, but you need to \
specify them.\
\>", "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9769693594324837`*^9, 3.976969405824705*^9}, {
   3.9769697637984505`*^9, 3.9769697762382603`*^9}, {3.976969837419836*^9, 
   3.9769698455114613`*^9}, {3.976969901678999*^9, 3.9769699594948444`*^9}, 
   3.9769703206257534`*^9},ExpressionUUID->"b8975ce2-b9f0-7546-95e7-\
d7f33124e5e0"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"G", "[", 
     RowBox[{"x_", ",", "y_", ",", "z_"}], "]"}], " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{
      RowBox[{
       SuperscriptBox["y", "2"], " ", "+", " ", "z"}], ",", " ", 
      SuperscriptBox["x", "3"], ",", " ", 
      RowBox[{"3", "y"}]}], " ", "}"}]}], " ", ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"define", " ", "a", " ", "vector", " ", "function"}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"h", "[", 
     RowBox[{"r_", ",", "theta_", ",", "phi_"}], "]"}], " ", "=", " ", 
    RowBox[{
     RowBox[{"3", 
      SuperscriptBox["r", "2"], 
      SuperscriptBox[
       RowBox[{"Cos", "[", "phi", "]"}], "2"], 
      RowBox[{"Sin", "[", "theta", "]"}]}], " ", "+", " ", 
     RowBox[{"4", 
      SuperscriptBox["r", "3"], 
      RowBox[{"Cos", "[", "phi", "]"}]}]}]}], ";"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
   "define", " ", "a", " ", "scalar", " ", "function", " ", "in", " ", 
    "spherical", " ", "coordinates"}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Grad", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"h", "[", 
     RowBox[{"r", ",", "theta", ",", "phi"}], "]"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"r", ",", "theta", ",", "phi"}], "}"}], 
    ",", "\"\<Spherical\>\""}], "]"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"Gradient", " ", "in", " ", "Spherical", " ", "coordinates"}], ",",
     " ", 
    RowBox[{
    "note", " ", "that", " ", "the", " ", "second", " ", "coordinate", " ", 
     "is", " ", "the", " ", "polar", " ", "angle"}], ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{
    "and", " ", "the", " ", "third", " ", "coordinate", " ", "is", " ", "the",
      " ", "azimuthal", " ", "angle"}]}], "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Curl", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"G", "[", 
     RowBox[{"x", ",", "y", ",", "z"}], "]"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"x", ",", "y", ",", "z"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", "Curl", "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Div", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"G", "[", 
     RowBox[{"x", ",", "y", ",", "z"}], "]"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"x", ",", "y", ",", "z"}], "}"}]}], "]"}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", "Divergence", "*)"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Laplacian", "[", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"h", "[", 
     RowBox[{"r", ",", "theta", ",", "phi"}], "]"}], ",", 
    RowBox[{"{", 
     RowBox[{"r", ",", "theta", ",", "phi"}], "}"}], 
    ",", "\"\<Spherical\>\""}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", "Laplacian", "*)"}]}]}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9769693594324837`*^9, 3.976969407300665*^9}, {
  3.976969847118271*^9, 3.9769698972021885`*^9}, {3.976969962842108*^9, 
  3.9769703093069744`*^9}, {3.993726375160446*^9, 3.993726390240438*^9}, {
  3.9937264569132032`*^9, 
  3.993726466793331*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"059b9c85-213e-b049-ada4-\
f5169da903fd"],

Cell[TextData[{
 "Being able to define functions in this way can be very helpful. Especially \
when it comes to creating nice plots, we will get to more of plotting in \
section III. \n\nAt this point, I also want to introduce you to a slightly \
different way to declare functions and variables using ",
 StyleBox["SetDelayed , ",
  FontWeight->"Bold"],
 "or the colon-equals (:=)  command.  With a normal equals sign, you cannot \
edit your function in any way once you have defined it. For example, suppose \
I have some quadratic polynomial ",
 Cell[BoxData[
  FormBox[
   TemplateBox[<|"boxes" -> FormBox[
       RowBox[{
         StyleBox["h", "TI"], 
         RowBox[{"(", 
           StyleBox["x", "TI"], ")"}], "\[LongEqual]", 
         StyleBox["a", "TI"], 
         SuperscriptBox[
          StyleBox["x", "TI"], "2"], "+", 
         StyleBox["b", "TI"], 
         StyleBox["x", "TI"], "+", 
         StyleBox["c", "TI"]}], TraditionalForm], "errors" -> {}, "input" -> 
     "h(x) = ax^2 + bx + c", "state" -> "Boxes"|>,
    "TeXAssistantTemplate"], TraditionalForm]],ExpressionUUID->
  "c928e2ef-e52e-3f46-aa87-0b7ebba8b164"],
 ". Where a, b, and c, are some constants. If I define the function first \
using equals (=), and then make changes to the constants, I the function will \
not change unitl I re-define it:"
}], "Text",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9769703275681095`*^9, 3.9769705158493385`*^9}, {
   3.976970645160671*^9, 3.976970742818342*^9}, {3.9769709209860477`*^9, 
   3.9769710108886166`*^9}, {3.976971416332304*^9, 3.976971419872059*^9}, 
   3.976971487787777*^9, {3.9772463042085876`*^9, 3.9772463056383553`*^9}, {
   3.977247239015276*^9, 3.977247343866049*^9}, {3.9772474233519287`*^9, 
   3.977247503522436*^9}, {3.977247536900219*^9, 3.9772476890582485`*^9}, {
   3.9772477217548714`*^9, 3.977247726900057*^9}, {3.977247770072487*^9, 
   3.977247770638674*^9}, {3.977247910907074*^9, 3.977248043123289*^9}, {
   3.9772480813347607`*^9, 3.9772482902495937`*^9}, {3.9772483698047256`*^9, 
   3.97724837634095*^9}, {3.9772484517469463`*^9, 
   3.97724848013591*^9}},ExpressionUUID->"e2c3cabc-6ce5-4044-b0bf-\
a5a7feed209c"],

Cell[BoxData[{
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"Clear", "[", 
   RowBox[{"a", ",", "b", ",", "c", ",", "h"}], "]"}], " ", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{"Clear", " ", "variable", " ", "names"}], "*)"}], 
  "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"give", " ", "a"}], ",", " ", "b", " ", ",", " ", 
    RowBox[{"and", " ", "c", " ", "values"}]}], "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"a", "=", "1"}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"b", "=", "2"}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{"c", "=", "3"}], ";"}], "\[IndentingNewLine]", 
 RowBox[{
  RowBox[{
   RowBox[{"h", "[", "x_", "]"}], "=", " ", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"a", " ", 
     SuperscriptBox["x", "2"]}], " ", "+", " ", 
    RowBox[{"b", " ", "x"}], " ", "+", " ", "c"}]}], 
  RowBox[{"(*", 
   RowBox[{
    RowBox[{"define", " ", "a", " ", "function", " ", "h", 
     RowBox[{"(", "x", ")"}], " ", "using"}], " ", "="}], 
   "*)"}]}], "\[IndentingNewLine]"}], "Input",
 CellChangeTimes->{{3.9769703275681095`*^9, 3.9769705158493385`*^9}, {
